Amendment to the Agreement between the European Atomic Energy Community ( Euratom ) and the Government of Canada of 6 October 1959 ( 1 ) for cooperation in the peaceful uses of nuclear energy in the form of an Exchange of Letters ( 78 / 217 / Euratom )
( 1 ) OJ No L 205 , 3 . 8 .
1165 / 59 . COMMISSION OF THE EUROPEAN COMMUNITIES
between the Kingdom of Belgium , the Kingdom of Denmark , the Federal Republic of Germany , Ireland , the Italian Republic , the Grand Duchy of Luxembourg , the Kingdom of the Netherlands , the European Atomic Energy Community and the International Atomic Energy Agency pursuant to Article III ( 1 ) and ( 4 ) of the Treaty on the Non-Proliferation of Nuclear Weapons ( 78 / 164 / Euratom )
CONSIDERING that the Kingdom of Belgium , the Kingdom of Denmark , the Federal Republic of Germany , Ireland , the Italian Republic , the Grand Duchy of Luxembourg and the Kingdom of the Netherlands , hereinafter referred to as &quot; the States &quot; , are signatories to the Treaty on the Non-Proliferation of Nuclear Weapons , signed in London , Moscow and Washington and entered into force on 5 March 1970 , hereinafter referred to as &quot; the Treaty &quot; ;
MINDFUL that Article IV ( 1 ) of the Treaty shall not be interpreted as affecting the unjust right of all Contracting Parties , while preserving equal treatment , in accordance with Articles I and II of the Treaty , to develop research , production and use of nuclear energy for peaceful purposes ;
MINDFUL that , pursuant to Article IV ( 2 ) of the Treaty , all Parties undertake to facilitate the widest possible exchange of equipment , materials and scientific and technological information for the peaceful uses of nuclear energy and are entitled to participate in it ;
RECALLING THAT , under the same paragraph , the Parties , which are in a position to do so , also cooperate with other States or international organizations in contributing , individually or jointly with , other States or international organizations , to the development of the application of nuclear energy for peaceful purposes , in particular in the territories of non-nuclear weapon States which are Parties ;
WHEREAS , pursuant to Article III ( 1 ) of the Treaty , any non-nuclear weapon State Party to the Treaty undertakes to adopt safeguards as defined in an agreement with the International Atomic Energy Agency , hereinafter referred to as &apos; the Agency` , to be negotiated and excluded , in accordance with the terms of its Statute , hereinafter referred to as &apos; the Statute` , and its safeguards system designed exclusively to verify the fulfilment of its safeguards under this Treaty in order to prevent nuclear energy being diverted from peaceful uses and used for nuclear weapons or other nuclear explosive devices ;
CONSIDERING that Article III ( 4 ) provides that non-nuclear-weapon States which are Contracting Parties shall , individually or jointly with other States , enter into agreements with them in accordance with the conditions of the Statute in order to comply with the requirements of this Article ;
WHEREAS the States of the European Atomic Energy Community ( Euratom ) , hereinafter referred to as &apos; the Community` , and common institutions of the European Communities have legal , entrusted and judicial powers which those institutions exercise independently in the fields within their competence and which can directly become effective within the legal systems of the Member States ;
CONSIDERING that , within this institutional framework , the Community has the task , in particular , to ensure , by means of appropriate safeguards , that nuclear materials are not diverted for the purposes for which they were not intended , and that , from the date of entry into force of the Treaty , such nuclear materials are therefore held on the territories of the States to the Community , by means of safeguards established by the Euratom Treaty , to ensure that there is no dispensing of any peaceful nuclear activity within the territories of States with any departure and special fissile nuclear material or other nuclear explosive devices ;
CONSIDERING that such safeguards include in particular the communication to the Community of the basic technical characteristics of nuclear installations , the maintenance and presentation of operating records to enable the Community to keep nuclear material accounts as a whole , inspections by Community officials and a system of penalties ;
CONSIDERING that the Community has the task of establishing links with other countries and with international organizations which are likely to promote progress in the use of nuclear energy for peaceful purposes and that it is expressly authorized to agree on specific safeguards obligations in an agreement with a third State or an international organisation ;
CONSIDERING that the Agency &apos;s international safeguards system , referred to in the Treaty , includes , in particular , provisions on the submission of investment data to the Agency , the maintenance of protocols , the submission of reports covering all nuclear materials subject to safeguards of the Agency , inspections by Agency inspectors , requirements for the establishment and maintenance of an accounting and control system for nuclear materials by a State , as well as measures for verification of non-diversion of such material ;
CONSIDERING that , in the light of the tasks entrusted to it by the Statutes and their relationship with the General Meeting and the United Nations Security Council , the Agency must be responsible towards the international community for ensuring that effective safeguards are applied under the Treaty ;
WHEREAS the States which were members of the Community at the time the Treaty is signed have decided that the safeguards provided for in Article III ( 1 ) of the Treaty should be laid down in a verification agreement between the Community , the States and the Organization and should be defined in such a way as not to affect the rights and obligations of the States and the Community ;
CONSIDERING that the Board of Governors of the Agency , hereinafter referred to as &quot; the Council &quot; , has approved comprehensive model regulations for the construction and content of the agreements required by the Treaty between the Agency and States to be used as the basis for the negotiation of safeguards agreements between the Agency and non-nuclear weapons States party to the Treaty ;
CONSIDERING that the Agency , as defined in Article IIIA 5 of the Statute , is empowered to take precautionary measures in response to requests made by the parties to bilateral or multilateral agreements or , where a State so requests , to apply their activities in the field of nuclear energy ;
CONSIDERING that it is a desire of the Agency , the Community and the States to avoid unnecessary duplication of effort in the field of safeguards ,
HAVE AGREED AS FOLLOWS :
PART I
ESTABLISHMENT
Article 1
States undertake , in accordance with Article III ( 1 ) of the Treaty , to adopt safeguards and safeguards for all peaceful nuclear activities carried out in their territories , under their sovereignty or under their control in any place in accordance with the provisions of this Agreement , for the whole of such nuclear activities , such safeguards being designed exclusively to verify that such material is not diverted to nuclear weapons or other nuclear explosive devices .
APPLICATION OF THE SAFEGUARD MEASURES
Article 2
The Organization shall have the right and shall be obliged to ensure that safeguards pursuant to this Convention are applied to all nuclear shipments and special fissile materials in any peaceful nuclear activity carried out in the territories of the States , under their sovereignty or under its control at any place , for the sole purpose of verifying that such safeguards are not diverted to nuclear weapons or to other nuclear explosive devices .
Article 3
( a ) The Community undertakes to cooperate with the Agency in the application of its safeguards to any peaceful nuclear activity carried out in the territories of States in accordance with the provisions of this Convention , in order to ensure that such departure and special fissionable material is not diverted to nuclear weapons or other nuclear explosive devices .
( b ) The Agency shall apply its safeguards measures in accordance with the provisions of this Convention in such a way as to enable it to verify the findings of the Community &apos;s safeguards system by ensuring that no nuclear material has been diverted from peaceful uses and has been used for nuclear weapons or other nuclear explosive devices .
Inspection by the Agency shall include independent measurements and observations by the Agency in accordance with the procedures laid down in this Agreement .
In its review , the organisation of the effectiveness of the Community guarantee system shall take due account of the provisions of this Agreement .
COOPERATION BETWEEN THE ORGANISATION , THE COMMUNITY AND THE STATES
Article 4
The Agency , the Community and the States shall cooperate , as far as each Party is concerned , to facilitate the implementation of the safeguards provided for in this Agreement and to avoid unnecessary duplication of effort in the field of safeguards .
IMPLEMENTATION OF THE SECURITY MEASURES
Article 5
The safeguards provided for in this Convention shall be implemented in such a way that : ( a ) they do not constitute an obstacle to economic and technological development in the Community or to international cooperation in the field of peaceful nuclear activities , including international transfers of nuclear materials ;
( b ) do not unduly interfere with peaceful nuclear activities in the Community , in particular in the operation of the installations ;
( c ) be consistent with prudent management practice as required for the economic and safe conduct of nuclear activities .
Article 6
( a ) The Agency shall take all steps necessary to protect industrial and industrial confidentiality and other confidential information acquired by it in the course of the implementation of this Agreement .
( b ) ( i ) The Agency shall not make public any information received by it in connection with the implementation of this Agreement , nor disclose it to any State , organisation or person , except for certain information relevant to the implementation of this Convention which may be communicated to the Council and to such staff of the Agency and which must be aware of its official duties related to safeguards measures ; this may , however , be done only to the extent necessary for the performance of the functions of the Agency in the implementation of this Agreement .
( ii ) aggregated information on nuclear materials subject to safeguards pursuant to this Agreement may be published upon a decision of the Council and with the consent of the States directly concerned or of the Community as far as either Party is concerned .
Article 7
( a ) In implementing safeguard measures under this Convention , full account shall be taken of technological development in safeguards , and all efforts shall be made to ensure the optimum cost-effectiveness and application of the principle of effective safeguards against fluxes of nuclear material subject to safeguards under this Convention by using instruments and other technical procedures on specific strategic points , as far as the technology in use is available or future .
( b ) the following procedures shall be applied in order to ensure maximum cost-effectiveness : ( i ) the geographical area of application as a means of determining material balance areas for accounting purposes ;
( ii ) statistical methods and sampling for assessing the fluxes of nuclear material ;
( iii ) concentration of verification procedures at the fuel cycle stages which relate to the production , processing , use and storage of nuclear material which could be manufactured without further nuclear weapons and other nuclear explosive devices and to the widest possible reduction of verification procedures for other nuclear materials , provided that this does not hinder the implementation of this Convention .
DISTRIBUTION OF INFORMATION TO THE ORGANISATION
Article 8
( a ) In order to ensure the effective implementation of safeguards under this Agreement , the Community shall , in accordance with this Agreement , provide the Agency with information on nuclear material subject to safeguards and on the characteristics of the Annexes relevant to the implementation of safeguards measures in respect of such material .
( b ) ( i ) The Agency shall only require the minimum level of information and data consistent with the performance of its tasks under this Agreement .
( ii ) information on installations shall be limited to the minimum necessary for the application of safeguards for nuclear material subject to safeguards under this Convention .
( c ) At the request of the Community , the Agency is prepared to examine investment information which the Community considers to be particularly vulnerable on the premises of the Community .
These data need not be materially provided to the Agency , provided that they remain easily accessible for further audits by the Agency on the premises of the Community .
INSPECTORS OF THE ORGANISATION
Article 9
( a ) ( i ) The Agency shall seek the consent of the Community and the States to the designation of States inspectors .
( ii ) If the Community objects either to a proposed nomination or at any time to a designation has been made , the Community organisation and the States shall propose one or more alternative designations .
( iii ) If , as a result of the repeated refusal by the Community to approve the designation of Agency inspectors , the inspections to be carried out under this Agreement are impeded , the Council shall discuss the refusal , after referring the matter to the Director General of the Agency , hereinafter referred to as the &apos; Director-General &apos; , with a view to taking the appropriate action .
( b ) The Community and the States concerned shall take the necessary steps to ensure that Agency inspectors can effectively carry out the tasks assigned to them by their Convention .
( c ) visits and activities of Agency inspectors shall be carried out in such a way as to minimise : ( i ) the potential annoyance and disruption to the Community and the States , and to the peaceful nuclear activities subject to inspection ;
( ii ) the protection of industrial secrecy and other confidential information brought to the attention of Agency inspectors is ensured .
PRIVILEGES AND EXEMPTIONS
Article 10
Each State shall apply the appropriate provisions of the Agreement on the Privileges and Immunities of the International Atomic Energy Agency to the Agency , including its assets , assets and funds , as well as to its inspectors and other officials performing tasks under this Agreement .
CONSUMPTION OR USE OF NUCLEAR MATERIAL
Article 11
The safeguards provided for in this Convention shall be terminated in respect of nuclear materials if the Community and the Agency establish that the material has been consumed or dilution in such a way that it is no longer usable for a nuclear activity relevant from the point of view of safeguards or has become practically irrecoverable .
EVIDENCE OF NUCLEAR MATERIALS FROM THE STATE
Article 12
The Community shall notify the Agency , in accordance with the provisions of this Agreement , of the transfer of nuclear materials from States subject to safeguards under this Agreement .
The safeguards provided for in this Convention in respect of nuclear materials shall cease as soon as the recipient State has taken responsibility for them as provided for in this Agreement .
The Agency shall keep records showing any communication and , where appropriate , the reapplication of safeguards to the transferred nuclear material .
PROVISIONS APPLICABLE TO NUCLEAR MATERIALS USED IN THE CASE OF NON-NUCLEAR ACTIVITIES
Article 13
In the event of the use of nuclear material subject to safeguards pursuant to this Convention in non-nuclear activities such as the production of alloys or lighting sites , the Community shall agree with the organisation of such use of such material on the conditions under which safeguards in respect of such material may be terminated in accordance with the provisions of this Convention .
NON-APPLICATION OF THE MEASURES RELATING TO COMMERCIAL MATERIALS SHOULD BE USED IN THE CASE OF NON-EXPERIENCE ACTIVITIES
Article 14
If a State , at its discretion , intends to use nuclear material for which safeguards are required under this Convention , in any nuclear activity which does not require the application of such safeguards , the following procedures shall be applied : ( a ) The Community and the State shall clearly inform the Agency of the activities and the State in this respect ; ( i ) that the use of such nuclear material in any non-prohibited military activity is not in contradiction with any obligation incumbent on it by the State to use such material solely in the event of a peaceful nuclear activity ;
( ii ) that , during the period of non-application of safeguards under this Agreement , the kerosene is not used for the production of nuclear weapons and other nuclear explosive devices .
( b ) The Agency and the Community shall establish rules to the effect that the safeguards provided for in this Agreement shall not be applied unless the nuclear material is used in any such activity .
The scheme shall , as far as possible , specify the length and circumstances in which such safeguards will not be applied .
In any event , the safeguards provided for in this Convention shall be reapplied once the nuclear material is reassigned to a peaceful nuclear activity .
The Agency shall be kept informed of the total quantity and composition of such material in the State or States concerned and of any transfer of such material from that State or States .
( c ) any such regulation is adopted in agreement with the organisation .
It shall declare its agreement as soon as possible ; it shall cover only matters such as , inter alia , time-frame and procedural provisions and reporting arrangements , but shall not include approval or knowledge of military activities covered by security , nor shall it apply to the use of nuclear materials .
FINANCIAL RECOGNITION
Article 15
The Agency , the Community and the States shall bear the costs incurred by each of them in fulfilling their respective obligations under this Agreement .
If , however , extraordinary costs are incurred by the Community , the States or persons under their jurisdiction as a result of a special request by the Agency , the Agency shall reimburse such costs , provided that it has made a prior determination to that effect .
In any event , the Agency shall bear the costs of any additional measurements and sampling required by Agency inspectors .
COMMUNITY FOR NUCLEAR SCHARES
Article 16
The Community and States shall ensure that the civil liability cover for nuclear damage , including any insurance or other financial security , can be invoked in accordance with their laws and regulations , to the organisation and its officials , for the purposes of the implementation of this Agreement , under the same conditions as nationals of States .
INTERNATIONAL ADMINISTRATIVE
Article 17
Any claim made by the Community or by any State to the Agency or to any State for damages , other than those resulting from a nuclear incident , arising out of the implementation of safeguards under this Agreement shall be dealt with in accordance with international law .
MEASURES RELATING TO THE INVESTIGATION OF THE NOTIFICATION
Article 18
If , on the basis of a report from the Director-General , the Council decides that a measure taken by the Community or by a State , as far as either Party is concerned , is essential and urgency to ensure , through verification , that nuclear materials which are subject to safeguards pursuant to this Agreement are not diverted to nuclear weapons or other nuclear explosive devices , the Council may request the Community or the State to take the necessary measures without delay , whether a dispute has been resolved in accordance with Article 22 .
Article 19
If , after considering the relevant information submitted to it by the Director-General , the Council finds that the Agency is not in a position to ascertain , by way of verification , that no nuclear material which must be covered by safeguards under this Agreement has been diverted to nuclear weapons or other nuclear explosive devices , it may report the reports provided for in Article XII , paragraph C , of the Statute and , where appropriate , take other measures as provided for in that Article .
In such stages , the Council shall take into account the extent to which the safeguards applied have been obtained and shall give the Community or the State , as far as both parties are concerned , any reasonable opportunity to provide the Council with the necessary security .
INTERPRETATION AND APPLICATION OF THE AGREEMENT AND SETTING OF ACTIVITIES
Article 20
At the request of the Agency , the Community or any State , consultations shall be held on matters arising from the interpretation or application of this Agreement .
Article 21
The Community and the States shall be entitled to request that matters arising from the interpretation or application of this Agreement be examined by the Council .
The Council shall invite the Community and the State concerned to participate in the discussion of such questions by the Council .
Article 22
Except in the event of any dispute arising out of the interpretation or application of this Agreement , any dispute which is not settled by negotiation or by any other procedure agreed by the organization , the Community and States shall , at the request of either Party , be submitted to an arbitral tribunal which shall be composed of five arbitrators .
The Community and the States shall appoint two arbitrators , the Agency shall also appoint two arbitrators , and the four arbitrators so designated shall elect a fifth , which shall be the chairman .
If , within 30 days of the request for arbitration , the Community and the States or the Agency have not designated two arbitrators , the Community or the Agency may request the President of the International Court of Justice to appoint such arbitrators .
The same procedure shall apply if , within thirty days of the appointment or appointment of the fourth arbitrator , the five arbitrators have not been elected .
A majority of the members of the arbitral tribunal shall have the right to vote and all decisions shall be approved by at least three arbitrators .
The arbitration procedure shall be determined by the arbitral tribunal .
The decisions of the arbitral tribunal shall be binding on the organisation , the Community and the States concerned .
TITLE I
Article 23
( a ) This Agreement shall enter into force for non-nuclear-weapon States which are parties to the Treaty and which become members of the Community : ( i ) when the State concerned notifies the Agency that its procedures for the entry into force of this Agreement have been completed ; and
( ii ) when the Community notifies the Agency that it is in a position to apply its safeguards measures in respect of that State for the purposes of this Agreement .
( b ) If the State concerned has concluded other agreements with the Agency on the application of safeguards provided by the Agency , the application of safeguards by the Agency pursuant to such agreements shall be suspended from the date of entry into force of this Agreement to the State for such time as this Agreement is in force , provided , however , that the State &apos;s obligation under such an agreement shall be retained to use such items in a way not conducive to military purposes .
AMENDMENTS TO THE AGREEMENT
Article 24
( a ) The Agency , the Community and the States shall consult each other , at the request of either Party , on an amendment to this Agreement .
( b ) All such amendments shall be subject to the approval of the organisation , the Community and the States .
( c ) The Director-General shall inform all Member States of the Organization of any amendment to this Agreement .
ENTRY INTO FORCE AND DURATION
Article 25
( a ) This Agreement shall enter into force on the date on which the Community and the States notify the Agency in writing that their procedures for entry into force have been completed .
The Director-General shall inform all Member States of the Organization of the entry into force of this Agreement .
( b ) This Agreement shall remain in force for such time as the States are parties to the Treaty .
PROTOCOL
Article 26
The Protocol annexed to this Convention shall form an integral part thereof .
The expression &quot; Convention &quot; used in this Convention means the Convention and the Protocol together .
PART II
INTRODUCTION
Article 27
The purpose of this part of the Agreement is to define as necessary the procedures to be followed for the application of the provisions of Part I concerning safeguards .
OBJECTIVES OF THE MEASURES IN QUESTION
Article 28
The purpose of safeguards procedures laid down in this Convention is to detect the timely discovery of diversion of significant quantities of nuclear material from peaceful nuclear activities for nuclear weapons and other nuclear explosive devices for unknown purposes and to dissuasive such diversion from the risk of early detection .
Article 29
In order to achieve the objective set out in Article 28 , material accountancy shall be used as a safeguard measure of fundamental importance , containment and surveillance as a major complementary measure .
Article 30
The technical completion by the Agency of the audits shall be carried out by means of a declaration specifying , for each material balance area , the quantity of material not proven for a given period , including the accuracy limits of the measurements specified .
COMMUNITY SUBSIDY SYSTEM
Article 31
In carrying out its inspections , the organisation referred to in Article 3 shall make full use of the Community guarantee system .
Article 32
The accounting and control system of the Community for nuclear materials established by this Convention shall be based on a classification in material balance areas .
In applying safeguards measures , the Community shall use the following procedures and measures and , if necessary , make provision for them to be specified and relevant in the supplementary Arrangements :
( a ) a system of measurement to determine the quantities of nuclear material derived , produced , dispatched , lost , or otherwise removed from the herd and the quantities of stocks ;
( b ) the evaluation of the feasibility and accuracy of the measurements and the assessment of the measurement uncertainty ;
( c ) procedures for identifying , verifying and evaluating differences in measurements made by consignors and consignees ;
( d ) procedures for taking physical inventories ;
( e ) methods for assessing accumulations of unmeasured stocks and unmeasured losses ;
( f ) a protocol and report system identifying , for each material balance area , the inventory of nuclear material and changes in that stock , including a material balance area exit and exit ;
( g ) arrangements to ensure that accounting procedures and arrangements are implemented correctly ;
( h ) procedures for reporting to the Agency in accordance with Articles 59 to 65 and 67 to 69 .
Article 33
The safeguards provided for in this Convention shall not apply to materials in mining or ore treatment .
Article 34
( a ) when uranium or thorium material which has not yet reached the nuclear fuel cycle as defined in subparagraph ( c ) , is exported directly or indirectly to a non-nuclear weapon State not party to this Agreement , the Community shall notify the Agency of the quantity , composition and destination of such material , unless it is specifically exported for non-nuclear purposes ;
( b ) where material containing uranium or thorium , which has not yet attained the nuclear fuel cycle as defined in subparagraph ( c ) above , is imported into States , the Community shall notify the Agency of the quantity and composition of the material , unless it is imported for specific non-nuclear purposes ;
( c ) when nuclear material , which by composition and purity is suitable for the production of fuel or for the enrichment of isotopic fuels , allows the installation or the process phase during which it is produced , or when such nuclear material , or other nuclear material produced in a subsequent phase of the nuclear fuel cycle , is imported into States , it shall be subject to the other safeguards provided for in this Agreement .
ASSESSMENT OF THE MEASURES
Article 35
( a ) The safeguards provided for in this Agreement shall be terminated for nuclear materials under the conditions set out in Article 11 ; however , if the conditions set out in Article 11 are not met , the Community considers that the recovery of nuclear material subject to safeguards under this Agreement from residues is not provisionally possible or desirable , the Agency and the Community shall consult each other on the application of appropriate safeguards .
( b ) The safeguards provided for in this Agreement shall be terminated in respect of nuclear materials subject to the conditions set out in Article 13 , provided that the organisation and the Community agree that such nuclear material will be practically irrecoverable .
RELIEF FROM THE SAID MEASURES
Article 36
At the request of the Community , the Agency shall exempt from safeguards under this Agreement :
( a ) special fissile materials , when used in grams or in smaller quantities as sensing components in instruments ;
( b ) nuclear material when used in non-nuclear activities in accordance with Article 13 , if such nuclear material is recovered ; and
( c ) plutonium with an isotopic concentration of plutonium-238 exceeding 80 % .
Article 37
At the request of the Community , the Agency shall exempt nuclear material which would otherwise be subject to safeguards pursuant to this Agreement , provided that the total quantity of nuclear material exempted in States pursuant to this Article is at no more than :
( a ) a total of one kilogram of special fissile material , which may consist of one or more of the following materials :
( i ) plutonium ,
( ii ) uranium with an enrichment of 0,2 ( 20 % ) , calculated by multiplying its weight by enrichment ;
( iii ) uranium with an enrichment of below 0,2 ( 20 % ) and above natural uranium , calculated by multiplying its weight by the five square of enrichment ;
( b ) a total of 10 metric tonnes of natural uranium and depleted uranium with an enrichment of more than 0,005 ( 0,5 % ) ;
( c ) 20 tonnes of depleted uranium with an enrichment of 0,005 ( 0,5 % ) ;
( d ) 20 metric tonnes of thorium
or greater quantities which may be determined by the Council for uniform application .
Article 38
In so far as nuclear materials released in combination with nuclear materials subject to safeguards pursuant to this Agreement are processed or stored , precautionary measures shall be taken to restore their safeguards .
SUPPLEMENTARY DEROGATIONS
Article 39
The Community shall establish with the Organization such supplementary arrangements as are necessary to the extent that the functions of the organisation under this Agreement are efficiently and effectively carried out , in particular , the manner in which the procedures established by the Agreement have to be applied .
The Subsidiary Arrangements may be extended or amended without amendment of this Agreement in agreement between the Agency and the Community .
Article 40
The Subsidiary Arrangements shall enter into force at the same time as , or as soon as possible after the entry into force of this Agreement ; the Agency , the Community and the States shall make all efforts to put these arrangements into force within 90 days of the entry into force of this Agreement ; an extension of this period shall be required to be agreed between the Agency , the Community and the States .
Whereas the Community will allow the Organization to obtain the information necessary for completing the Subsidiary Arrangements ; whereas after the entry into force of this Agreement , the Organization will be entitled to apply the procedures laid down therein to nuclear material included in the inventory provided for in Article 41 , even if supplementary arrangements have not yet entered into force ;
PART OF THE PRINCIPLES
Article 41
On the basis of the initial report referred to in Article 62 , the Agency shall draw up a summary inventory of all nuclear material subject to safeguards under this Agreement , irrespective of its origin , and shall keep that inventory on the basis of subsequent reports and the results of verifications made .
Copies of the inventory shall be made available to the Community at intervals to be agreed .
between the European Economic Community ( EEC ) and its Member States Belgium , Denmark , the Federal Republic of Germany , France , Ireland , Italy , Luxembourg , the Netherlands , the United Kingdom ( Member States ) , of the one part , and the International Development Organisation ( Organisation ) , of the other part
WHEREAS ( a ) Whereas the EEC has decided to contribute to the special action programme established by the Conference on International Economic Cooperation in order to remedy the immediate needs of individual non-income countries , the development of which is hampered by general rescuing problems of concentration ;
( b ) The EEC has requested the organisation to manage a special account ( special action account ) for which it is eligible , for the implementation of the aforementioned Decision , equal to the equivalent in US dollar dollar of the equivalence , which is separate from all other accounts and assets of the organisation and is to be used for loans ( special share-loans ) , which will be in addition to the amount of the programme provided by the organisation on the basis set out below , both under programmes and under programmes and for projects carried out during the commitment period of the special action account in each country to which they may be granted ;
( c ) the objective of the EEC and the Member States shall be to commitment to the total amount of the contribution made by the Member States within six months of the entry into force of the Agreement and to issue loans as far as possible within two years of the entry into force of the Agreement and to enable the organisation to achieve this objective ;
( d ) The EEC and the Agency have consulted each other on the proposed implementation and management of this Agreement and on the commitments made to ensure a broad and balanced geographical distribution under this Agreement ;
Whereas to this end the organization has submitted to the EEC a table showing how it intends to apply the criteria laid down in this Agreement ,
HAVE THE PARTIES TO THE FOLLOWING UNDERTAKING :
ARTICLE I
Establishment and management of the Special Accountancy Account
Section 1
The Organization shall establish a special account , called the &quot; special action account &quot; , consisting of the funds which Member States contribute to the Special Action Account pursuant to this Agreement ; this account shall be maintained and used by the organisation as the administrator ; this account shall be maintained and used ( hereinafter referred to as the &quot; administrator &quot; ) only for the purpose and in accordance with the provisions of this Agreement .
The special account shall be kept separately and separately from all other Agency accounts and assets .
Section 2
Each Member State shall pay , as a contribution to the special action account , an amount in its national currency corresponding to the amount in US dollars at the time of signature of this Agreement , hereinafter referred to as the amount ( in Mill . USD ) * 15,90 * Belgium * 11,28 * Federal Republic of Germany * 119,08 * France * 56,48 * Ireland * 1,04 * Italy * 34,92 * Luxembourg * 0,50 * Netherlands * 30,80 * United Kingdom 115,00 * 385,00 *
Section 3
Contributions shall be paid as follows : ( a ) The payment shall be made in the form of cash or interest-bearing notes of the Member State which must , at the request of the State concerned , be paid into Order as manager of the special account and be deposited with the depository of the organisation in that country ;
( b ) Payment shall be made in two instalments : ( i ) the first amount shall be at least 45 % of the contribution , within 30 days of the entry into force of this Agreement or by any other date agreed between the EEC and the administrator ;
( ii ) the second amount , equal to the balance of the contribution , at 1 January 1979 or at any other time agreed between the EEC and the administrator , taking into account the time required for the approval of the annual budgets .
( c ) Any Member State may , on request , make payments before the above dates .
Section 4
The liquidator shall , in accordance with normal practice of the organisation , draw approximately proportional drawings on the cash or vouchers in order to cover expenses for special participation loans and to ensure that the special account is duly balanced .
ARTICLE II
Use of the special account
Section 1
All sums credited to the special account shall be used exclusively by the liquidator in accordance with the provisions of the EEC and by members of the organisation of low-income and invalid * needs , in particular the least developed among them ( 1 ) and the most disadvantaged developing countries , whose development prospects have been significantly reduced by external factors reflecting general resour-flow problems and whose debt service difficulties may cause special loans .
The granting of these loans shall be such as to enable the liquidator , in accordance with the conditions laid down in the EEC , to base themselves on the following factors :
( i ) the relative poverty of the developing country concerned and its long-term growth potential ;
( iii ) the extent to which international economic factors have contributed to the present and foreseeable economic problems of the country ;
( iv ) trends and future prospects of the country &apos;s exposure ;
( v ) the ability of the country to ensure imports of products essential to the development process ;
( vi ) the composition and trend of the debt service of the country and its other borrowing capacity on loan terms without any advantage ; and
( vii ) the extent to which problems encountered by the countries concerned can be addressed by contributions from other sources .
Section 2
Each special loan shall be used to finance a clearly defined and rapid development programme or project ( including a sectoral project ) , assessed , authorised and managed in accordance with the procedures and practices applicable to credits financed by the organisation &apos;s ordinary resources , taking into account the objective of additionality referred to in point ( b ) of the preamble to this Agreement .
The resources of the special action account may not be used in place of ordinary resources of the International Bank for Reconstruction and Development ( Bank ) or of the Organization which , under a loan or credit , are linked to a programme or project already approved by the Bank or organisation &apos;s directors on the date of entry into force of this Agreement .
Section 3
Apart from Section 4 , special repayment loans shall be subject to the same repayment conditions as are generally applicable to development loans granted by the organisation and shall therefore be reimbursable for 10 free years in each case .
The loans granted under this scheme are not remunerated .
Section 4
Special loans shall be granted in one or more currencies of the Member States and shall be reimbursable in those currencies .
Section 5
The administrator shall be entitled , in accordance with the usual procedures in the Organization , to reimburse the services which it provides under this Agreement to each beneficiary of a special loan , to pay to the organisation an application fee equal to three quarters of a process ( 3 / 4 ) of 1 % per year of the amount of lending capital outstanding at that time in a currency acceptable to the organisation .
Amounts intended for payment of that tourist shall be paid directly to the organisation which retains them .
Section 6
Any special loan must be identified by a separate loan agreement between the beneficiary country and the liquidator , indicating in particular the origin of the funds .
Section 7
Revenue accruing from any special loan may be used to cover expenditure in the currency of the recipient country or in respect of goods or services manufactured or provided : ( i ) in a Member State ; ( ii ) in developing countries which are members of the organization and which , in accordance with the procedure laid down by the liquidator at the time of granting the loan , could be the beneficiaries of a special loan .
Section 8
Any repayment of special capital loans shall be made to the special intervention account and the amount repaid in this way in the currency of a Member State shall be repaid by the administrator to the Member State concerned as soon as possible after it has been received .
The Agency shall not be liable for any loss of the repayment of special participation loans .
ARTICLE III
Reports ; consultations
Section 1
The administrator shall inform the EEC of the projects and programmes approved by the Directors pending full implementation of all special measures loans .
During the period of disbursement of the special loans , the liquidator shall inform the EEC every three months of the development of the special loan and the expenditure incurred .
The administrator shall forward to the EEC , as soon as possible after the end of the Agency &apos;s financial year , detailed accounts of the special account with an opinion of the Agency &apos;s external auditors on that account .
After paying the special loans in full , the administrator shall send the EEC as soon as possible a detailed report on projects and programmes financed by the special intervention account .
Section 2
The liquidator shall establish and maintain adequate records and accounts showing contributions to the special intervention account , the commitments to be financed from the accounts , the amounts received from and paid out of the account and the repayments made to the Member States .
Section 3
The EEC and the administrator shall cooperate closely to achieve the objectives of this Agreement .
To this end , the EEC ( represented by the Commission of the European Communities ) and the administrator shall from time to time exchange views on the state of the special account , on the continuation of programmes or projects financed by special operations and on any other matter relating to the provisions of this Agreement , until the funds of the special action account have been fully incurred .
ARTICLE IV
Termination ; distribution
Section 1
If this Agreement has not entered into force on 31 December 1978 , or on such date as may be agreed upon by the EEC and the Organization , the Agreement and all obligations of the Parties resulting therefrom shall lapse immediately .
Section 2
If the total amount of all special participation loans received by the beneficiaries is repaid and refunded to the Member States in accordance with Article II ( 8 ) of this Agreement , this Agreement and all the obligations of the parties resulting therefrom shall be terminated immediately .
ARTICLE V
Final provisions
Section 1
This Agreement shall be approved by each Member State and by the EEC in accordance with the procedural provisions of each Party .
Section 2
The Governments of the Member States shall notify the General Secretariat of the Council of the completion of the procedures concerning them .
The General Secretariat shall forward these notifications to the Organization , together with a notification of the appropriate approval of this Agreement by the EEC .
Section 3
This Agreement shall take effect and shall enter into force on the first day of the month following the date of receipt by the Organization of the said notifications .
Section 4
This Agreement is drawn up in duplicate in the Danish , Dutch , English , French , Italian and Dutch languages , each of these texts being equally authentic .
Whereas the Agreement in the form of an exchange of letters amending Annex A to Protocol 1 to the Agreement between the European Economic Community and the Swiss Confederation ( 1 ) should be concluded , HAS ADOPTED THIS REGULATION :
Article 1
between the European Atomic Energy Community and the Swiss Confederation in the field of controlled thermonuclear fusion and plasma physics
THE EUROPEAN ATOMIC ENERGY COMMUNITY , hereinafter referred to as &quot; Euratom &quot; , represented by the Commission of the European Communities , hereinafter referred to as &quot; the Commission &quot; ,
AND THE SWISS CONFEDERATION , hereinafter referred to as &quot; Switzerland &quot; , represented by the Swiss Federal Council , hereinafter referred to as &quot; Federal Council &quot; ,
WHEREAS since 1959 , as part of a long-term common programme covering all activities in the field of controlled thermonuclear fusion and plasma physics in Euratom , multiannual research and training programmes in the field in question have been implemented with a view to industrial manufacture and marketing of reactors in the controlled thermonuclear fusion and are implemented , inter alia , by means of association contracts and an Agreement on the promotion of staff exchanges , the last of which is the fourth five-year programme for the period 1976 to 1980 ;
The programme includes the establishment of a large experimental plant , the project JET ( Joint European Torus ) , the construction and the operation of which are entrusted to a Joint Undertaking in accordance with Chapter V of the Euratom Treaty , hereinafter referred to as &quot; Joint Undertaking JET &quot; .
Whereas Switzerland has been engaged in research in the field of controlled thermonuclear fusion and plasma physics for a number of years and is best familiar with the area in question ;
Whereas , pending the practical use of controlled thermonuclear fusion , it is in the interest of the Contracting Parties to this Agreement to consolidate their relevant efforts in order to avoid unnecessary duplication and to speed up their respective research activities , which have resulted in a higher level of priority due to the energy crisis ,
HAVE AGREED AS FOLLOWS :
A. Subject matter of the Agreement
Article 1
Whereas the purpose of this Agreement is to enable each Contracting Party to make the best possible use of the resources made available for mutual research , to avoid unnecessary duplication and , accordingly , to achieve the common objective of such research ; whereas the cost-effective electricity generation through the use of the controlled nuclear fusion action is more rapidly achieved through a combination of its research efforts ;
Article 2
2.1 .
In order to achieve the objective of this Agreement , the Parties shall associated their respective research programmes , defined in Annexes I and II to this Agreement , hereinafter referred to as the &quot; Euratom programme &quot; and &quot; Swiss programme &quot; .
In order to ensure effective cooperation , the Swiss programme shall implement the long-term objectives and forms of cooperation of the Euratom programme ; it shall , after examination by the institutions referred to in Articles 5 to 10 and 16 of this Agreement , be extended or amended in such a way as to include , where appropriate , new activities relevant to the Euratom programme .
Whenever the Contracting Parties adopt a new programme , it shall replace the programme ( s ) listed in Annexes I and II to this Agreement .
The association provided for in paragraph 1 shall be implemented : - the appropriate participation of each of the Contracting Parties in the preparation and implementation of the other &apos;s programmes ,
- the exchange of personnel between the relevant laboratories in the Member States of Euratom , Switzerland and third States with which Euratom has concluded an agreement similar to this Agreement , hereinafter referred to as &quot; associated third countries &quot; , and the laboratories participating in the Euratom programme ,
- the mutual financing of programmes ,
- reciprocal right of access to the scientific and technical results of the respective programmes .
2.2 .
Within the framework of the objective of this Agreement , Switzerland shall participate in the JET project .
B. Legal instruments to achieve the objective of the Agreement
Article 3
3.1 .
In order to implement the association provided for in Article 2 ( 1 ) of this Agreement , the Parties shall conclude an association contract , hereinafter referred to as the &quot; Association Treaty &quot; , which shall as far as possible be equivalent to the contract concluded between the Commission and the States and undertakings , or persons , hereinafter referred to as the &quot; associated institutions &quot; , with a view to implementing the Euratom programme .
For the same purpose , Euratom shall ensure that Switzerland participates , with effect from the date of entry into force of this Agreement , in the Agreement on the promotion of staff exchanges concluded between the Commission and the associated institutions , hereinafter referred to as &quot; Staff Exchange Agreement &quot; .
3.2 .
With a view to participation in the JET project , Switzerland shall , from the date of entry into force of this Agreement , belong to the Joint Undertaking JET whose statutes it accepts .
3.3 .
Furthermore , Euratom shall ensure that Switzerland is entitled to contract parties for each contract the purpose of which is governed by this Agreement , with the exception of association contracts or other similar contracts concluded by Euratom during the period of validity of this Agreement .
C. Institutions in pursuance of the objective of the Agreement
Article 4
4.1 .
The institutions responsible for implementing the association provided for in Article 2 ( 1 ) of this Agreement are described in Articles 5 to 10 of this Agreement and in the Association Treaty .
4.2 .
The organs of the Joint Undertaking JET are described in the Statutes of that undertaking .
Article 5
The association agreement shall in particular include the establishment of a Steering Committee , the competent representative of the Commission and the Federal Council .
The functions of the Steering Committee shall be : - to implement the association contract ,
- lay down the detailed rules for the programmes to be covered by the contract ,
- to monitor the development of research and to ensure that best possible results are achieved in accordance with the objectives of this Agreement .
Article 6
6.1 .
Switzerland shall be represented by a maximum of two delegates within the liaison group set up under the Euratom programme , hereinafter referred to as the &quot; VG &quot; .
The VG , which shall provide for the exchange of information and cooperation on all matters relating to programmes and activities in the field of the Euratom programme in progress or planned , shall carry out this task in respect of all research and development activities covered by this Agreement .
It shall in particular promote cooperation and coordination between the associated institutions and shall , for the interest of both Parties , apply their T * to the common objective , as defined in the Euratom programme , Swiss programme , and as well as to the common objective set out in Article 1 of this Agreement , taking due account of scientific and technological developments in the world .
6.2 .
In accordance with its rules of procedure , one or more Swiss representatives from the advisory groups established under the Euratom programme shall appoint , whenever the competent Swiss authorities so request , one or more such representatives .
The advisory groups submitting UN research proposals with a view to ensuring that the appropriations allocated to the Euratom programme provide the best possible scientific results shall carry out this task in respect of all research and development referred to in this Agreement .
Article 7
7.1 .
Switzerland shall be represented on the Committee of Directors established under the Euratom programme by the Director of one of the participating laboratories .
The Committee of the Directors responsible for monitoring the implementation of the Euratom programme and responsible for making the best use of the capacity of the laboratories involved in the work carried out under the programme shall carry out this task in respect of all research and development activities covered by this Agreement .
In particular , it shall ensure the best use of staff and the exchange of the same between laboratories involved in the implementation of the Euratom programme and the Swiss programme .
7.2 .
One Swiss representative shall be entitled to attend the meetings of all the coordination committees established under the Euratom programme .
The coordination committees , which shall make appropriate proposals to the Committee of Directors for the best use of the resources , staff and knowledge and skills available to the laboratories involved in the implementation of the Euratom programme , shall carry out these tasks in the field of all research and development covered by this Agreement .
Article 8
Switzerland shall be represented on the Consultative Committee , hereinafter referred to as the CCF .
The BAF shall comprise a representative from each Member State of Euratom , Switzerland and each associated third country responsible for the core and energy research .
At the request of the Commission , the BAF shall advise the Commission on the implementation of the programme and on possible changes in the guidelines , as well as on the preparation of future programmes and the definition of their overall size , coordination and integration of national mergers at Community level .
Article 9
The opinions of the BAF , the VG , the Executive Sector Committee , the advisory groups and the coordination committees are of an advisory nature .
The opinion of the UN on the priority actions shall be compulsory , and shall also apply to the Committee of Directors in the field of staff exchanges .
Article 10
The representatives of the two Parties shall participate in the work of any technical and advisory body or any administrative body established for the purposes of this Agreement .
D. Financial and tax provisions of the Agreement
Article 11
11.1 .
The financial contribution of Switzerland to the Euratom programme pursuant to this Agreement shall be fixed annually at an amount which shall be the same as that of the share represented by Euratom in the cost of the Euratom programme , as that of the total gross domestic product of Switzerland and of the total gross domestic product of Euratom and Switzerland in the previous year .
In the case of JET , this financial contribution concerns the participation of Euratom in the Joint Undertaking as soon as it is established .
Furthermore , Switzerland transfers a sum to be fixed in accordance with the financial provisions of the Statute of this Joint Undertaking to the Joint Undertaking JET .
11.2 .
The financial contribution , Euratom to the financing of the work carried out under the Association Treaty and the Staff Agreement shall be calculated on the same basis as is normally used to calculate Euratom contributions to the financing of the work arising from the corresponding contracts .
11.3 .
At the beginning of each year , the Commission shall inform the Federal Council of the amount intended to cover expenditure under the Euratom programme for that year .
The Federal Council shall pay the Commission the amount due under this Article as follows : 7 / 12 before 15 January and 5 / 12 before 15 January .
The other methods of payment applicable to the financial contributions from Switzerland and Euratom under this Article shall be as set out in Annex III to this Agreement .
Article 12
12.1 .
Switzerland shall take all necessary measures to ensure that Euratom is exempted from customs duties and other charges and from import restrictions in respect of that part of the property financed by Euratom to be used in Switzerland for the activities covered by this Agreement .
12.2 .
Goods imported into or acquired in Switzerland shall not be disposed of in that country , whether for payment or free of charge , unless otherwise authorised by the Federal Council .
12.3 .
Commission officials within the meaning of Article 1 of the Staff Regulations of officials of the European Communities whose salaries , wages and emoluments paid by the Communities are subject to Community tax and who engage in Swiss activities covered by this Agreement , as well as Swiss persons subject to the aforementioned Staff Regulations and participating in such activities in the territory of the Member States of Euratom , shall be exempt from national taxes on salaries , wages and emoluments .
These exemptions shall not apply to pensions and pensions paid to such persons .
E. Provisions of the Agreement on access to knowledge
Article 13
13.1 .
The arrangements for access to knowledge relating to the association provided for in Article 2 ( 1 ) of this Agreement are set out in Articles 14 and 15 of this Agreement , in the Association Treaty and in the Agreement on the exchange of staff .
13.2 .
The provisions on access to knowledge relating to Switzerland &apos;s participation in the Joint Undertaking JET are set out in Article 14 of this Agreement and in the Statutes of the Joint Undertaking .
Article 14
14.1 .
The right of access by either Party to knowledge of the other Party is an essential element of this Agreement .
14.2 .
This right is guaranteed by : - rules on the dissemination of knowledge and patents ,
- the exchange of personnel between participating laboratories in Euratom , Switzerland and associated third countries ,
- appropriate account being taken of undertakings in Euratom , Switzerland and associated third States when awarding contracts for the implementation of the two associated programmes , in accordance with the principle of best use of the amounts so used .
Article 15
15.1 .
Information collected during the period of validity of this Agreement in Euratom and in the associated institutions in the activities of controlled thermonuclear fusion and plasma physics shall be communicated to Switzerland and to persons or undertakings carrying out research or production activities in Switzerland on grounds of access to such knowledge under the same conditions as Member States , persons or undertakings of Euratom .
15.2 .
Knowledge arising from research activities carried out in Switzerland under this Agreement shall be communicated to the Member States of Euratom and the associated third States and to persons or undertakings carrying out research or production activities in a Member State of Euratom or an associated third State justifying access to such knowledge .
The Contracting Parties shall communicate such knowledge to other States , persons or undertakings only if an agreement to that end is reached between the Parties , unless such persons or undertakings are engaged in research or production activities in Switzerland which justify access to such knowledge .
15.3 .
Where the knowledge referred to in paragraphs 1 and 2 of this Article is protected by patents , such patents may be used by the Member States of Euratom , Switzerland , the associated third countries and by persons or undertakings established in the countries concerned for research purposes in pursuance of the objectives of this Agreement .
The Member States of Euratom , Switzerland , the associated third States and the persons or undertakings established in the countries concerned may , on reasonable terms , be granted licences or sublicences for the use of such patents for industrial or commercial purposes , in so far as the parties are entitled to grant such licences or sublicences .
15.4 .
The knowledge arising from the activities of Euratom , the associated institutions and Switzerland before the entry into force of this Agreement shall be made available to the States , persons or undertakings to which the knowledge referred to in paragraphs 1 and 2 may be communicated , to the extent necessary for the use of the knowledge referred to in those subparagraphs .
patents arising out of the activities referred to in this point shall be made available to States , persons or undertakings which may obtain a licence or a sub-licence in respect of the patents referred to in paragraph 3 of this Article to the extent necessary for the use of such licences or sublicences .
15.5 .
This Article shall not affect inventions or their legal counsellors &apos; rights conferred by national law .
15.6 .
The Contracting Parties shall refrain from any act which could affect the patentability of inventions resulting from the activities referred to in paragraphs 1 and 2 of this Article .
F. General provisions and final provisions of the Agreement
Article 16
16.1 .
A Joint Committee , to be known as the &quot; Euratom / Switzerland Merger Committee &quot; , to which the representative of the Commission and representatives of the Federal Council shall be attached .
16.2 .
The Euratom / Switzerland Committee shall be responsible for the proper implementation of the Agreement .
It shall examine all measures likely to improve cooperation under the Agreement and keep up to date with regard to the progress of the work .
16.3 .
If either Contracting Party considers that the other Contracting Party has failed to fulfil an obligation under this Agreement , it shall forthwith inform the Swiss Contracting Committee thereof .
16.4 .
The Euratom / Switzerland Committee may , for the purpose of carrying out its tasks , make recommendations , on the basis of the opinion of the ESA , to the competent authorities of the Euratom countries and Switzerland responsible for adopting the programmes and budgets in the fields of research covered by this Agreement .
16.5 .
The Euratom / Switzerland Committee shall adopt its own rules of procedure .
The Presidency shall be held alternately by the Contracting Parties in accordance with the rules of procedure of the Merger Committee , Euratom / Switzerland .
16.6 .
The Euratom / Switzerland Merger Committee shall meet at the request of either Contracting Party , and at least once a year .
Article 17
17.1 .
Any dispute arising out of the interpretation or application of this Agreement shall be submitted to an arbitral tribunal at the request of either Party .
17.2 .
The arbitral tribunal referred to in paragraph 1 of this Article shall be constituted on a case-by-case basis .
It shall be made up of three members .
Each Contracting Party shall appoint one member and these two members shall designate a third member , who shall be the Chairman of the arbitral tribunal .
If one of the Contracting Parties has not appointed a member within two months of the date on which the referral to arbitration has been requested in a dispute , or if , within one month of the election of the second member of the arbitral tribunal , the President of the International Court of Justice has not agreed on the appointment of the third member , the latter shall be invited by the Contracting Party or the Contracting Parties to appoint that member .
17.3 .
The latter shall determine the procedure of the arbitral tribunal .
The arbitral tribunal shall decide by majority vote .
Its decisions shall be binding .
17.4 .
Each Contracting Party shall bear the costs of its own member in the arbitration procedure ; the costs of the Presidency and the other costs shall be borne in equal shares by both Contracting Parties .
Article 18
The Annexes to this Agreement shall form an integral part thereof .
Article 19
19.1 .
This Agreement shall be approved by the Parties in accordance with their own procedures .
It shall enter into force when the parties have notified each other that the procedure necessary for this purpose has been implemented .
19.2 .
This Agreement shall be concluded for the duration of the Euratom programme referred to in Article 1 and shall be automatically renewed in accordance with further relevant decisions of Euratom .
In the event that such further decision is taken , the extension shall apply to the duration of the new programme , which replaces the Euratom programme mentioned in Annex I. This Agreement shall be deemed not to be terminated if only delays occur in the adoption of a further Euratom programme .
Before any decision is taken concerning the adoption of a new Euratom programme , the Contracting Parties shall consult each other within the bodies referred to in Articles 5 to 10 and 16 of this Agreement .
19.3 .
Either Party may denounce this Agreement at any time , provided that six months &apos; notice is given .
