A. Letter from the Bank for International Settlements
Sir ,
BZ could conclude stand-alone credit agreements with the central banks of creditors if the banks so request .
The agreements could be concluded up to the total amount of the contribution paid by the creditor to the mechanism , up to a total limit of 2,725 billion units of account , representing 50 % of all future stand-by ceiling in the Member States .
The details of the standardisation agreements should be regulated between the BIZ and the relevant central bank .
However , the conditions currently stated below are certain conditions which would be acceptable to the use of BIZ .
For each stand-by loan , BIZ would first assume an obligation for two years , with the possibility of extensions without , however , exceeding a total of five years .
When opening the credits and extending them , BIZ would calculate a credit commission .
Moreover , it would be agreed that the first drawings will not be made before the end of one month after the conclusion of the Standing Agreement so that the Bank can make the necessary adjustments to its own liquidity .
drawings were made in currencies available in the BIZ at the conclusion of the agreement and would be very likely to take place in USD ; they would cover periods to be negotiated taking into account the bank ’ s funds , which would be expected to be three months or six months .
The terms and conditions would be similar to those applied by BZ to transactions carried out under similar conditions at the time , i.e. interest rates would largely be in line with market rates .
Normally , interest rates are likely to be slightly higher than &quot; Liboron &quot; rates only .
